{
  "local_port": 43592,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some less fictioned movie everyone must watch?",
  "response": "It sounds like you're interested in movies that are grounded in real-life events, true stories, or documentaries\u2014films that are less fictionalized and offer a more authentic portrayal of reality. These movies can be incredibly impactful, providing insights into historical events, personal journeys, social issues, and more. Here are some highly recommended \"less fictioned\" movies that everyone should consider watching:\n\n### **1. Schindler's List (1993)**\n- **Genre:** Historical Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Directed by Steven Spielberg, this powerful film tells the true story of Oskar Schindler, a German businessman who saved over a thousand Polish Jews during the Holocaust by employing them in his factories.\n- **Why Watch:** It's a poignant portrayal of courage and humanity amidst one of history's darkest periods.\n\n### **2. Apollo 11 (2019)**\n- **Genre:** Documentary\n- **Synopsis:** This documentary offers an immersive look into the 1969 Apollo 11 mission, using newly discovered footage and audio recordings to present the first moon landing.\n- **Why Watch:** It provides a stunning, authentic glimpse into one of humanity's greatest technological achievements.\n\n### **3. The Social Network (2010)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Directed by David Fincher, the film explores the creation of Facebook and the legal battles that followed, focusing on its founder, Mark Zuckerberg.\n- **Why Watch:** It offers insight into the complexities of friendship, ambition, and the digital age's impact on society.\n\n### **4. 13th (2016)**\n- **Genre:** Documentary\n- **Synopsis:** Directed by Ava DuVernay, this documentary analyzes the intersection of race, justice, and mass incarceration in the United States.\n- **Why Watch:** It's a thought-provoking examination of systemic racism and its enduring effects.\n\n### **5. Spotlight (2015)**\n- **Genre:** Investigative Journalism Drama\n- **Synopsis:** This film follows the Boston Globe's \"Spotlight\" team as they uncover the widespread child sex abuse by Catholic priests and the subsequent cover-up within the Church.\n- **Why Watch:** It highlights the importance of investigative journalism in exposing institutional corruption.\n\n### **6. Into the Wild (2007)**\n- **Genre:** Adventure Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Directed by Sean Penn, the movie is based on the true story of Christopher McCandless, who travels across North America seeking a life of solitude in the Alaskan wilderness.\n- **Why Watch:** It's a compelling exploration of freedom, self-discovery, and the human spirit.\n\n### **7. The Imitation Game (2014)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Thriller\n- **Synopsis:** Starring Benedict Cumberbatch, the film portrays Alan Turing's efforts to crack Nazi Germany's Enigma code during World War II and his tragic personal life.\n- **Why Watch:** It celebrates Turing's genius and sheds light on the injustices he faced.\n\n### **8. The Pursuit of Happyness (2006)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Will Smith stars as Chris Gardner, a struggling single father who overcomes homelessness to become a successful stockbroker.\n- **Why Watch:** It's an inspiring story of perseverance and dedication against all odds.\n\n### **9. Erin Brockovich (2000)**\n- **Genre:** Legal Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Julia Roberts plays Erin Brockovich, a legal assistant who uncovers a massive environmental scandal involving contaminated water in a small town.\n- **Why Watch:** It showcases the impact one determined individual can have on environmental justice.\n\n### **10. Blackfish (2013)**\n- **Genre:** Documentary\n- **Synopsis:** This documentary focuses on Tilikum, an orca held by SeaWorld, and examines the consequences of keeping such intelligent creatures in captivity.\n- **Why Watch:** It raises important questions about animal welfare and the ethics of marine parks.\n\n### **11. Hidden Figures (2016)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Drama\n- **Synopsis:** The film tells the untold story of three African-American women mathematicians who played crucial roles at NASA during the early years of the U.S. space program.\n- **Why Watch:** It highlights the contributions of marginalized individuals in shaping history.\n\n### **12. Free Solo (2018)**\n- **Genre:** Documentary\n- **Synopsis:** This gripping documentary follows rock climber Alex Honnold's attempt to conquer El Capitan in Yosemite National Park without any ropes or safety gear.\n- **Why Watch:** It's an exhilarating look at human determination and the pursuit of extreme challenges.\n\n### **13. Catch Me If You Can (2002)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Crime Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Directed by Steven Spielberg and starring Leonardo DiCaprio and Tom Hanks, the film is based on the true story of Frank Abagnale Jr., who successfully performed cons worth millions of dollars before his 19th birthday.\n- **Why Watch:** It's a fascinating tale of deception, adventure, and the cat-and-mouse game between a con artist and an FBI agent.\n\n### **14. Spotlight (2015)**\n- **Genre:** Investigative Journalism Drama\n- **Synopsis:** Follows the Boston Globe's investigative team as they uncover a massive scandal of child molestation and cover-up within the local Catholic Archdiocese.\n- **Why Watch:** It underscores the power of journalism in holding institutions accountable.\n\n### **15. The Big Short (2015)**\n- **Genre:** Biographical Comedy-Drama\n- **Synopsis:** This film delves into the events leading up to the 2008 financial crisis, highlighting the individuals who foresaw the collapse and capitalized on it.\n- **Why Watch:** It provides an engaging and informative look at complex financial systems and their vulnerabilities.\n\nThese films not only entertain but also educate and inspire, making them essential viewing for anyone interested in stories that reflect real-world experiences and events.",
